"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831146","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Secretary of State has made no such estimate.</p><p>In respect of “twin track” minerals applications, the Hon Member may wish to know that under section 70B of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990, a local planning authority can decline to determine an application for planning permission. This may be when it has been made either on the same day as a similar application or when particular conditions apply in relation to a similar application, such as where that similar application is under consideration by the Secretary of State on appeal and the Secretary of State has not issued his decision. <br> <br> An application is similar to another application if a local planning authority think that the development and the land to which the applications relate are the same or substantially the same.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-05T14:07:58.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831146/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831146/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-26","Planning Permission: Quarrying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to Sections 70a and 70b of the Town and County Planning Act 1990 (as amended), what estimate he has made of the number of overlapping and subsequent minerals applications, commonly known as twin track minerals applications, that have been submitted since 2011.","false","Biography information for Lee Rowley","North East Derbyshire","Lee Rowley","125154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831147","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-02","<p>The UK is proud to be a founding supporter of the Robert Carr Civil Society Networks Fund since 2012 and has pledged up to £9million to support the grassroots response for inadequately served groups affected by HIV.</p><p>DFID assesses the outcomes achieved by the Robert Carr Civil Society Networks Fund annually, as we do for all our programmes, and the reviews are available on the DFID Development Tracker at <a href="https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/</a>.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-02T11:27:14.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831147/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831147/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-26","Robert Carr Civil Society Networks Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the outcomes achieved by the Robert Carr Civil Society Networks Fund with Government funding.","false","Biography information for Paul Scully","Sutton and Cheam","Paul Scully","125155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831148","Department for Education","false","2018-02-06","<p>Between 2013 and 2018 70 Pupil Referral Units (PRUs) have applied to convert to academy status, as shown in table 1 below. Please note that schools may apply more than once. Where this has been the case, we have taken the most recent application date.</p><p> </p><p>During the same period, 76 PRUs have converted to alternative provision academies, as shown below. No PRU has opened as any other form of special school.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1. Number of Pupil Referral Units that applied to convert to an academy, and number of PRUs opened as alternative provision academies 2013-2018</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year of application</p></td><td><p>Number of applications from PRUs</p></td><td><p>Number of PRUs opened as alternative provision academies[1]</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>70</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>76</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Internal Management Information and Get Information about Schools extract (January 2018).</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] This includes PRUs that converted as either a sponsored or converter alternative provision academy and some may not have submitted an application.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-02-06T17:17:57.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831148/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831148/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-26","Pupil Referral Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many pupil referral units have applied to convert to academy status in each of the last five years; and how many pupil referral units have converted to (a) alternative provision academies and (b) other forms of special school in that same period.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","125156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831149","Department for Education","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Department will publish full details of the review, including timetables and how views can be submitted, in due course.</p><p>The externally led review of exclusions practice will consider how schools use exclusion overall and how this impacts on pupils, particularly why some groups such as those eligible for free school meals, those with special educational needs and disabilities, looked after children, children in need and pupils from certain ethnic groups are more likely to be excluded from school.</p><p>The Department publishes exclusion rates by characteristic annually. The most recent release can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/permanent-and-fixed-period-exclusions-in-england-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/permanent-and-fixed-period-exclusions-in-england-2015-to-2016</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-05T17:22:23.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831149/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831149/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-26","Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to press release Prime Minister launches world-leading project on impact of ethnicity on everyday life, published on 10 October 2017, what the timetable is for his Department's external review of exclusions; and if he will list the groups disproportionately likely to be excluded on whose experiences that review will focus.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","125157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831150","Department for Education","false","2018-02-05","<p>The framework of core content for initial teacher training (ITT) was published in July 2016 alongside two reports on behaviour management content and national standards for ITT mentors. These reports further support providers to meet the framework’s requirements.</p><p>In addition, Ofsted uses the framework of core content when making judgements regarding the quality of training and the leadership and management of an ITT partnership. 99% of all ITT partnerships inspected by Ofsted were judged to be either good or outstanding at their most recent inspection.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-05T17:23:25.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831150/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831150/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-26","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to ensure providers of initial teacher meet the requirements set out in the Framework of core content for initial teacher training.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","125158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831151","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-31","<p>Work to integrate Sunderland County Court into Sunderland Magistrates’ Court is expected to be completed by the end of May 2018. The Sunderland County Court building will be closed once the integration is complete.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-31T17:43:03.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831151/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831151/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-26","County Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South and the hon. Member for Sunderland Central from the former Minister of State for Courts and Justice on 11 December 2017, what the timetable is for the closure of the Sunderland County Court building.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","125159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831152","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-31","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service currently has no plans to alter any arrangements regarding the future of the Sunderland court estate.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-31T17:52:13.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831152/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831152/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-26","Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South and the hon. Member for Sunderland Central from the former Minister of State for Courts and Justice on 11 December 2017, whether a decision has been made on the future of Sunderland Court Estate.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","125160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831153","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-31","<p>Social Security and Child Support Tribunal appeal hearings will be integrated into the Sunderland Magistrates’ Court building by the end of March 2018.</p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-31T17:42:58.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831153/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/831153/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-26","Magistrates' Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South and the hon. Member for Sunderland Central from the former Minister of State for Courts and Justice on 11 December 2017, whether he has plans to integrate Social Security and Child Support Tribunal services into the Sunderland Magistrates’ Court building.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","125161"
