"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830500","Women and Equalities","false","2018-01-31","<p>A range of factors are explored when considering whether to nominate a candidate for an election to a body such as the CEDAW Committee. A decision on whether to nominate a UK candidate for the next CEDAW Committee membership elections will be made by 7 March.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-01-31T13:34:02.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830500/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830500/answer",,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-01-25","UN Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 January (HL4558), why the UK has never made a nomination to the UN Committee for Ending Discrimination against Women; and what consideration they have given to making a nomination in recognition of the centenary of the Representation of the People Act 1918 extending voting rights to women.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL5108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830501","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-02","<p>Based on information provided by water companies, the Environment Agency assesses that around 3% of water put into public supply is used and not paid for. This includes water taken legally and water that is stolen. Water taken legally includes public supplies for which no charge is made, such as firefighting and training.</p><p> </p><p>The ratio of the 3% taken legally to illegally is unknown.</p><p> </p><p>Companies can take action through the courts against water thieves. For example, in September 2017, Thames Water took Kilgannon Street Care to court, who admitted 12 offences under the Water Industry Act 1991 and was ordered to pay more than £5,000 in fines and costs.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-02-02T12:59:02.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830501/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830501/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-25","Water: Theft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their latest assessment of the problem of water theft in the UK’s water industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830502","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-01-30","<p>The Government has provided a range of explanatory material to accompany the EU (Withdrawal) Bill in its passage through Parliament. We will update this material periodically to reflect any changes to the Bill as necessary.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-01-30T17:23:14.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830502/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830502/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-25","European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department plans to update its website entitled Information about the Withdrawal Bill to reflect the decision of the House to pass amendment 7 to clause 9 of the EU (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Mr Chris Leslie","125050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830503","Home Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Government works closely with industry on resilience issues which include understanding better the impact of cable theft on communications networks. In relation to cables that are made of, or contain metal, the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 provides a strong legislative basis for helping to prevent and tackle such theft by making it more difficult for criminals to dispose of stolen metal.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-02-06T16:37:12.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830503/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830503/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-25","Telecommunications Cables: Theft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their latest assessment of the problem of cable theft in the UK’s communications industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830504","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-07","<p>As of 5th February, the latest figures from the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea show that 92 households from Grenfell Tower and Grenfell Walk remain in emergency accommodation, which includes those living in hotels, serviced apartments and some who are living with friends and family. The Council has assured me that no residents from Grenfell Tower or Walk are living in bed and breakfast accommodation.</p><p>A total of 60 households from Grenfell Tower or Walk have moved into interim accommodation. The Council has committed that the interim homes offered to residents are self-contained, fully furnished, big enough for each family and are not in a high rise building and the Council is providing advice and help to residents in setting up their interim home.</p><p>We expect the Council to do whatever is necessary to ensure households can move into settled homes as swiftly as possible, but to do so sensitively and taking into account individual needs. We are working closely with the Council to support them in delivering their commitment to provide survivors with a permanent new home in social housing within one year of the fire.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-07T13:17:57.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830504/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830504/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-25","Grenfell Tower: Fires","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many survivors of the Grenfell Tower fire are still living in hotels, bed and breakfasts or other temporary accommodation.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830505","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>Bahrain is a multi-religious country with all religions co-existing. Freedom of religion is guaranteed by the Bahraini constitution. Members of all religions and communities continue to play an important part in Bahraini society with representation in the Shura Council and elected chamber of Parliament, Diplomatic service, as senior Government Ministers and officials, and other leading areas of society</p><p>The United Kingdom continues to encourage Bahrain's successful efforts on religious freedoms.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-02T14:43:31.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830505/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830505/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-25","Bahrain: Religious Freedom
","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the level of religious freedom in Bahrain; and what steps the Government is taking to promote and protect the right of freedom of religion in that country.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","125051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830506","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-05","<p>The UK has an inflation target, not an exchange rate target, and the government does not express a view on the level of the exchange rate. The value of sterling adjusts flexibly in response to economic conditions and market forces.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-02-05T16:23:01.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830506/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830506/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-25","Exchange Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the performance of sterling in the last 12 months, in comparison to the dollar, the euro and the yen.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830507","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-07","<p>We have provided financial support to local authorities for data collection and reporting on cladding on high rise private residential buildings. The total amount transferred to local authorities was £289,000.</p><p>The government will also consider financial flexibilities for local authorities to undertake essential fire safety work to make buildings safe. We have not turned down any requests for such flexibilities.</p><p>Building owners are responsible for funding fire safety measures.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-07T13:15:32.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830507/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830507/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-25","High Rise Flats: Insulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much money they have paid to local authorities since the Grenfell Tower fire to help with the recladding of tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830508","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-30","<p>My Department has recently been in discussion with the Law Commission, Network Rail and the Office of Rail and Road regarding legislative proposals for level crossings. We will be making an announcement shortly on our proposed next steps.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-30T11:03:46.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830508/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830508/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Level Crossings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent progress his Department has made on preparing legislative proposals in response to the recommendations of the Law Commission's report on Level Crossings, published on 25 September 2013.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","125052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830509","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-02","<p>As part of its long-term strategy , the Department for Transport has contracted longer trains and more frequent services, allowing rail commuters into Leeds to benefit from a 52% increase in the number of seats in the morning peak on TransPennine Express (TPE) trains, and a 37% increase on Northern trains. To more widely improve connectivity in West Yorkshire we have contracted various service benefits to be delivered by December 2019 for Leeds, Bradford and the surrounding area, which include:</p><p> </p><p>Leeds:</p><ul><li>3 extra TPE services per day to Hull, with some longer trains</li><li>Brand new electric trains to Skipton and Ilkley to provide extra capacity, with more carriages on the busiest services</li><li>Local Northern services to Doncaster will operate using more modern trains and will increase to an hourly service on Sundays</li><li>Quicker journeys to Sheffield and Nottingham as part of high-quality Northern Connect network – to Nottingham in 1h 40mins</li><li>Increased frequency to provide 4tph to Harrogate between 0700 and 1900 in combination with Virgin East Coast, plus enhanced evening and Sunday services. The additional Northern services to Harrogate will be up to 20% faster</li><li>Increase to 7 trains per day to Lancaster via Skipton - with times better suited to commuters.</li><li>One extra train departing for Settle and Carlisle between 1600 and 1900, and two extra services on Sundays</li><li>Stopping service to Sheffield via Moorthorpe will double in frequency to hourly on Sundays</li><li>Later evening service to Cattal, Hammerton, Poppleton and York</li><li>New station at Kirkstall Forge with 1tph to Leeds</li><li>New station at Apperley Bridge with 2tph to Leeds</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p>Bradford:</p><ul><li>A new direct link to Wakefield, Sheffield, Chesterfield and Nottingham as part of the Northern Connect network, with at least 10 services per day in each direction operated by brand new trains</li><li>One extra train per hour to Manchester, with a significantly enhanced evening and Sunday service</li><li>New direct links to Liverpool and Manchester Airport, with an hourly service to each using brand new trains as part of the Northern Connect network</li><li>Increased frequency on Sundays to Skipton and Ilkley, with hourly trains</li><li>A new station at Low Moor to receive 1tph to Bradford.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Other locations will also benefit, including:</p><ul><li>Halifax – an additional service every hour to Manchester, Bradford and Leeds</li><li>Huddersfield - Northern stopping services to Leeds via Dewsbury replaced by an additional 1tph between Manchester and Leeds on TPE, improving punctuality by using better accelerating trains</li><li>Knottingley and Pontefract Monkhill - Doubled frequency of trains to Leeds with 2tph; Sunday services increase to 1tph</li><li>Pontefract Tanshelf, Featherstone, Streethouse - existing services to Wakefield extended through to Leeds, and they will also run in alternate hours on Sundays</li><li>Slaithwaite, Marsden, Greenfield and Mossley will enjoy a direct hourly TPE service to Leeds.</li><li>Cross Gates, Garforth, East Garforth and Micklefield will receive 2tph to Leeds on Sundays.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Department does not compare train services from area to area as assessments are conducted on the needs of the individual areas they serve.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-02-02T11:23:48.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830509/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830509/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Railways: West Yorkshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their latest assessment of train connectivity and train services in West Yorkshire, in comparison with other parts of England.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830510","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-02","<p>In the last year Ministers and officials have met over 2000 stakeholder organisations, including over 600 businesses at a series of stakeholder events. After the last General Election, we set up a business advisory group with an EU Exit focus that’s attended by senior Government ministers, to give higher priority to companies’ concerns in the EU exit negotiations. We want to agree the terms of a time-limited implementation period as soon as possible - giving businesses across the UK certainty.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-02T15:01:03.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830510/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830510/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Industrial Products","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to convene a meeting with representatives from the industrial product supply sector to address concerns relating to uncertainty over the proposed transition period after the UK leaves the EU, in particular (1) how long that transition period will last, and (2) the parameters of rights and regulations that will apply during that period.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Kinnoull",,"The Earl of Kinnoull","HL5115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830511","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-01","<p>Defra officials recently met Iceland’s Managing Director to discuss Iceland’s plan to eliminate plastic in its own brands by 2023.</p><p> </p><p>In December 2017, the Secretary of State chaired a roundtable with representatives from across the plastic sector to discuss reducing the amount of packaging produced and increasing the level of recycling.</p><p> </p><p>In November I wrote to a number of major retailers to ask about their packaging choices for specific products.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-02-01T12:29:08.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830511/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830511/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-25","Plastics: Packaging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with major supermarkets on the reduction of plastic use.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","125053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830512","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-08","<p>The December guidelines published by the European Council point to the shared desire of the EU and the UK to make rapid progress on an implementation period, with formal talks beginning very soon. We have been clear that this should be based on the existing structure of EU rules and regulations, during which the UK and the EU would continue to have access to one another’s markets on current terms.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-02-08T17:02:26.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830512/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830512/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-25","Public Sector: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the EU Commission Notice issued on 10 January stating that EU public procurement rules will cease to apply to the UK from 30 March 2019.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Kinnoull",,"The Earl of Kinnoull","HL5116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830513","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-05","<p>We have proposed an implementation period, based on the existing structure of EU rules and regulations. During this period the UK’s and the EU’s access to each other’s markets will continue on current terms. It is in the interests of both the UK and the EU to agree the terms of this period as quickly as possible, in order to provide vital certainty to businesses and citizens. We are confident that there is broad agreement between the UK and EU positions on the implementation period, and that we will come to an agreement by March.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-02-05T15:16:19.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830513/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830513/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-25","UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, as part of their Brexit negotiating strategy, they are seeking to ensure that during the transition period following the UK’s withdrawal from the EU all current trading terms will continue to apply for UK business trading with the EU27; and whether they intend to offer such reciprocal obligations on the UK as would be required to enable this to happen.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Kinnoull",,"The Earl of Kinnoull","HL5117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830514","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-01","<p>The New Enterprise Allowance does not provide support or funding for Multi-Level Marketing businesses.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","125056","2018-02-01T16:57:36.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830514/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830514/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Direct Selling: New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much money from the new enterprise allowance has been granted to people to participate in multi-level marketing schemes with (a) Herbalife UK, (b) Forever Living, (c) Younique, (d) Arbonne, (e) Lifetree World, (f) Jamberry, (g) Amway, (h) JuicePlus, (i) Stella & Dot, (j) Ariix (k) Maelle and (l) other organisations in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","125054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830515","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-05","<p>The EU and UK have both said that EU rules and regulations should continue to apply during the implementation period.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>During this strictly time-limited implementation period, the UK and the EU would continue to have access to one another’s markets on current terms, and the UK would take part in existing security measures.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In the Implementation Period, the UK will take steps to pave the way for the UK’s independent trade policy after we exit. As such, we will be able to negotiate our own free trade agreements, although we would not bring them into effect until after the implementation period has concluded.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The government is committed to seeking continuity during the Implementation Period in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU Free Trade Agreements or other EU preferential arrangements.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-02-05T15:17:54.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830515/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830515/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-25","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, as part of their Brexit negotiating strategy, they intend UK products to be treated, during the transition period, as EU content for the purposes of (1) EU regulatory structures, and (2) trade agreements held by the EU with other countries.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Kinnoull",,"The Earl of Kinnoull","HL5118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830516","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-08","<p>In my answer to HL4312 I confirmed that there had been no ministerial visits to HMP Liverpool in the last year. I also advised of the prison visits undertaken by ministers in 2016 and 2017 in my response to HL4313. Information on ministerial visits before that time would need to be retrieved from manual records at the prison or from archived records held by the Ministry of Justice. This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-02-08T16:29:28.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830516/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830516/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-25","Liverpool Prison","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Keen of Elie on 5 January (HL4312) and 24 January (HL4477), when was the most recent ministerial visit to HM Prison Liverpool prior to the Prisons Minister's visit on 22 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Lee of Trafford",,"Lord Lee of Trafford","HL5119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830517","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has already made decisions on some cases and the relevant local authorities have been informed. We are still reviewing the other cases received, and will give local authorities a decision shortly. Each request requires detailed review against the criteria issued in August 2017 and in some cases further information has been needed, on matters such as school forum decisions and local consultation, before a decision can be taken.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are required to issue budgets to all their maintained schools by 28 February 2018, and we have committed to ensuring that all decisions on disapplications are communicated in time for local authorities to meet that deadline.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-30T17:36:45.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830517/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830517/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-25","Dedicated Schools Grant: Kingston upon Thames","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when his Department plans to make a decision on whether to grant the request  from Kingston Borough Council to disapply guidelines on the ring-fenced dedicated schools grant for the 2018-19 financial year.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","125055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830518","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-01","<p>We are in discussions with Stagecoach to ensure the needs of passengers and taxpayers will be met in the short term whilst laying the foundations for introduction of the East Coast Partnership from 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We expect to provide additional services between Lincoln, Harrogate, Bradford and London from May 2019. It remains our intention to deliver additional services to Middlesbrough and Huddersfield. Virgin Trains East Coast has contingent rights to run services from London to Middlesbrough from May 2020 and firm rights from May 2021.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-02-01T11:57:45.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830518/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830518/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","East Coast Rail Franchise","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the announcement by the Secretary of State for Transport on 29 November that the Stagecoach–Virgin partnership would cease to operate the East Coast Rail franchise in 2020, whether they expect that the commitments in the original franchise that were due to be met before 2020 will continue to be met; and in particular, whether they expect (1) direct services from Middlesbrough to London, (2) two-hourly direct weekday services between Bradford, Harrogate, Lincoln and London, and (3) new direct peak-time services between Huddersfield and London, to be established by May 2019.","false","Biography information for Lord Shutt of Greetland",,"Lord Shutt of Greetland","HL5120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830519","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Government is committed to supporting the construction sector to increase the gender diversity of its workforce. The Construction Industry Training Board (CITB) has taken practical steps by developing a ‘Be Fair’ framework, including freely available fairness and inclusion training modules for construction firms. In addition, CITB’s careers hub, ‘Go Construct’, provides online guidance and case studies for prospective employees - and employers - on a range of diversity topics, including gender.</p><p> </p><p>Nevertheless, more work is needed to improve the diversity of the construction sector. We are engaging with the industry as to how further improvements can best be achieved and we expect to see this agenda being driven forward through the Sector Deal for construction that was announced in our Industrial Strategy White Paper on 27 November.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-05T13:28:11.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830519/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830519/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Construction: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to encourage the creation of jobs for women in the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830520","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-01","<p>Under Local Government Act 2003, local authorities have the freedom to borrow and invest, without government consent, provided that their borrowing is affordable. As part of this ‘prudential’ framework, every local authority is required to set its own borrowing limit, which must be approved by full Council or the equivalent at least annually. The Government has backstop powers to set national borrowing limits at times of economic crisis, which would override the normal prudential freedoms. These powers have never been used.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-01T16:40:32.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830520/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830520/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-25","Local Government: Borrowing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether there is an cap on the borrowing that local authorities can undertake; if so, what the basis for this cap is; and what powers they have to step in should borrowing be excessive, including through the Public Works Loan Board.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830521","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-01","<p>The New Enterprise Allowance does not provide support or funding for Multi-Level Marketing businesses.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","125054","2018-02-01T16:57:36.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830521/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830521/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Direct Selling: New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions what proportion of the new enterprise allowance has been granted to people wishing to participate in multi-level marketing schemes with (a) Herbalife UK, (b) Forever Living, (c) Younique, (d) Arbonne, (e) Lifetree World, (f) Jamberry, (g) Amway, (h) JuicePlus, (i) Stella & Dot, (j) Ariix (k) Maelle and (l) other organisations in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","125056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830522","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-02","<p>A ‘CE mark’ is a numerical code which indicates that a product conforms to the requirements set out in the relevant EU legislation. In some cases the product will also have been tested by a notified body before the manufacturer labels the product with a CE mark. The Government recognises the valuable role that third party testing plays in giving business, consumers and the public, confidence in products on the market. We have been engaging with manufacturers and testing bodies across the country to understand their concerns.</p><p> </p><p>The UK wants to ensure that any approvals, registrations, certificates and authorisations issued by a third party (whether a private entity or a public agency) prior to exit should continue to be recognised as valid by both markets after the UK’s withdrawal.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-02T15:00:10.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830522/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830522/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Certification Quality Marks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the effect of Brexit on agencies that provide CE-Certification.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL5123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830523","Department for International Trade","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Department for International Trade welcomes the National Audit Office’s report, which found that DIT was implementing delivery plans for its priority EU Exit work streams in line with the Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) guidance, and we will continue to work closely with DExEU to deliver them.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-02-05T17:21:51.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830523/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830523/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-25","Overseas Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they intend to take to address the findings of the National Audit Office report Implementing the UK's Exit from the European Union: The Department for International Trade, published on 25 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL5124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830524","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>The report will be published shortly.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-01-30T17:06:08.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830524/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830524/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-25","Students: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 18 December 2017 to Question HL3865 on Students: Finance, what the timetable is for quality checks on the Student Income and Expenditure Survey 2014-15 to be completed.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","125057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830525","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-07","<p>In any negotiation there are careful judgements about when and how to set things out in public and we will keep under review the best way of doing this.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government has been clear that it retains the ambition of ensuring the City of London remains a global financial centre.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We are continuing to engage extensively both with industry and with EU partners to hear their views and set out our arguments. The Prime Minister welcomed a number of senior representatives from the financial services sector to No.10 Downing Street in January 2018 to discuss the opportunities and challenges for the financial sector posed by Brexit.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-02-07T15:57:37.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830525/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830525/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-25","Financial Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to publish a position paper on financial services and Brexit; and what steps they are taking to provide clarity on the implications of Brexit to the financial sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL5125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830526","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government constantly monitors the health of all of its strategic suppliers and reviews its contingency plans as necessary. Carillion publicly issued profit warnings on three occasions.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-02-20T14:12:12.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830526/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830526/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-25","Carillion: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they received any forewarnings of financial difficulties at Carillion PLC.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL5126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830527","Department for Education","true","2018-01-30","<p><ins class="ministerial">Figures for educational psychologists in service in all local authorities in 2017 are not available until Summer 2018.</ins></p><p>The attached table provides the number of Educational Psychologists (EPs) that were reported as being directly employed by each local authority in November 2016. The list excludes local authorities where EP provision has been outsourced or the provision has been shared with other local authorities. It would also be open to academies and free schools to obtain their own provision.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-30T17:51:10.757Z","2018-02-07T09:06:40.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830527/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830527/answer","125058 - Full-time equivalent educational psychologists in service in state funded schools..xlsx","No. Educational Psychologists","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830527/answer","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830527/answer/previousversion/38114","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830527/answer/previousversion/38114","125058 - Full-time equivalent educational psychologists in service in state funded schools..xlsx","Number of Educational Psychologists ","60","Education","Education","2018-01-25","Educational Psychology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many educational psychologists were employed in all local authorities in 2017.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","125058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830528","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-08","<p>There is no requirement for Health Professionals to inform claimants of their qualifications when they first meet and introduce themselves. If asked about qualifications it would be at the Health Professional’s discretion whether or not to disclose this information.</p><p>All Health Professionals undertaking PIP assessments must be registered with the appropriate professional body such as the General Medical Council or Nursing and Midwifery Council and have at least 2 years post full-registration experience. Details of any Health Professional’s primary qualifications are publically available on the websites of the relevant governing body.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2018-02-08T12:34:01.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830528/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830528/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether Personal Independence Payment assessors who are asked by claimants what professional qualifications they hold are obliged to inform those claimants.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL5127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830529","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Prosperity Fund and the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund both spent Official Development Assistance (ODA) in 2016, according to Statistics on International Development. The Empowerment Fund is also a cross-government fund with funding classified as ODA but there was no ODA spending from this fund in 2016 which is the latest year for which statistics are currently available.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-02-06T17:19:25.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830529/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830529/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which cross-government funds include funding classified as Overseas Development Assistance.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830530","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-30","<p>The financial framework for Control Period 6 has not yet been set and will be finalised by the ORR later this year. The Statement of Funds Available published in October 2017 confirmed Government’s intent to change some of the mechanisms by which it funds Network Rail, but other aspects of the financial framework remain under active development by the ORR. The Department for Transport has regular engagement with the ORR on the development of the financial framework, in light of Government’s strong interest in this issue.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-30T11:16:38.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830530/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830530/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Railways: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions took place between his Department and the ORR prior to the establishment of the financial framework for Control Period 6; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","125059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830531","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Conflict, Stability and Security Fund spent £601 million of official development assistance (ODA) in 2016. This accounts for 4.5 per cent of the UK total UK ODA.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-02-06T17:16:49.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830531/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830531/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of the UK's total Overseas Development Assistance is disbursed via the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830532","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Regulatory Periodic Review process (PR18) is ongoing and is designed to consider the appropriate funding, charging and work to be undertaken by Network Rail in Control Period 6. Government continues to input its views into this process, which will consider the risks faced by Network Rail before concluding with a Determination, expected October 2018.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-31T11:17:26.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830532/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830532/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the business risks faced by Network Rail in Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","125060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830533","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Statement of Funds Available, published 12 October 2017 made clear that, “Network Rail will not take loans or issue bonds from Government or any Third Party to fund the HLOS (“High Level Output Specification” for Control Period 6). In addition, Network Rail must refer to the ‘Network Rail Framework Agreement’ before entering into any financial transactions which may be classified as borrowing.”</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-31T11:27:15.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830533/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830533/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Network Rail will be permitted to borrow in Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","125061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830534","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-30","<p>Whilst we currently have no such explicit plans, there is nothing to prevent bidders including infrastructure proposals that could provide passenger benefits or improved efficiencies in their franchise bid.</p><p> </p><p>And as the Secretary of State recently announced, we are also setting out our plans for a new generation of regional rail partnerships between the public and private sector. When these plans are developed, we will bring them to the back to this House.</p><p> </p><p>We will also be looking to see what lessons can be learnt in this area from the Welsh Government’s procurement which includes Core Valley Lines infrastructure.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-30T15:41:37.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830534/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830534/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to include enhancements to infrastructure in future rail franchise bids; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","125062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830535","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-30","<p>The Department publishes ‘Income-related benefits: estimates of take-up’ statistics annually.</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics, which cover 2009/10 to 2015/16, are published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-related-benefits-estimates-of-take-up-financial-year-201516" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-related-benefits-estimates-of-take-up-financial-year-201516</a></p><p> </p><p>These statistics provide estimates of take-up, by caseload and expenditure, of the following income-related benefits only (other benefits are available but no take-up estimates are calculated):</p><ul><li>Pension Credit</li><li>Housing Benefit</li><li>Income Support and Employment and Support Allowance (income-related)</li><li>Jobseeker’s Allowance (income-based)</li></ul><p> </p><p>They also provide the total and average amounts of benefit claimed and unclaimed for each of these benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates for 2010/11 and 2011/12 were not produced; the estimates for 2016/17 will be published in May/June this year.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-30T14:27:50.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830535/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830535/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the total value of unclaimed benefits in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","125063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830536","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-31","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-31T14:47:58.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830536/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830536/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-25","Mental Illness: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many and what percentage of prisoners who received a custodial sentence suffered from one or more mental health conditions in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","125064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830537","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-01","<p>Data on the number of homes with a Housing Health and Safety Rating System (HHSRS) Category 1 hazard, by tenure are published on the Department's website for the years 2008, 2013, and 2015. The data shows that the number of homes with a category 1 hazard declined between 2008 and 2015 by 22 per cent in the private rented sector, and by 57 per cent in the social rented sector.</p><p>This information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/627668/Potential_stock_improvements_report_Chapter_1_housing_quality.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/627668/Potential_stock_improvements_report_Chapter_1_housing_quality.xlsx</a></p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-02-01T16:03:19.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830537/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830537/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-25","Rented Housing: Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of homes with category 1 hazards were owned by (a) local authorities, (b) social landlords and (c) private landlords in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","125065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830538","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-01","<p>Mandatory licensing applies to Houses in Multiple Occupation (HMOs) that are three or more storeys and occupied by five or more persons forming at least two separate households.</p><p>The Department considers mandatory licensing of these larger HMOs as being effective in raising property conditions and standards. This is why we consulted on extending its scope and we will, subject to parliamentary clearance, bring forward new legislation requiring all HMOs (subject to a few exceptions) with five or more occupiers to have a local authority licence.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-02-01T15:29:11.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830538/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830538/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-25","Multiple Occupation: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the mandatory licensing scheme for houses in multiple occupation.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","125066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830539","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-30","<p>The costs of branded medicines are controlled by the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme and the statutory scheme for branded medicines. Liothyronine is an unbranded generic medicine. For unbranded generic medicines, the Department encourages competition between suppliers to keep prices down. In primary care, community pharmacies are incentivised to source products at the lowest possible cost and in secondary care, competitive tenders ensure value-for-money to the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>Liothyronine is currently the subject of an investigation by the Competition and Markets Authority, which has provisionally found that the single supplier of the product abused its dominant position to overcharge the NHS by millions for liothyronine tablets. A provisional decision does not necessarily lead to an infringement decision. Where companies have breached competition law, the Department will seek damages and invest that money back into the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>Medicines legislation requires that only medicines licensed for use in the United Kingdom can be marketed in the UK.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","125070","2018-01-30T17:14:17.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830539/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830539/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-25","Liothyronine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the money accrued to the public purse in relation to liothyronine under the (a) the voluntary Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme and (b) the statutory scheme; and when those payments were made.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","125067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830540","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-30","<p>The Department has made no assessment. It is for local clinical commissioning groups in conjunction with local providers to make decisions on implementing NHS England’s guidance on liothyronine and, as part of their decision making, to determine the resources available to implement any change.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-30T17:10:32.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830540/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830540/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-25","Liothyronine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on the level of caseloads of consultant endocrinologists as a result of changes to the prescription of liothyronine.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","125068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830541","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>Government is leading a review to reflect our ambition to strengthen Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs). This will enable them to prioritise investment in order to bring a strong business voice to local decision-making to drive sustainable private sector-led growth and job creation. This is testament to our belief that business and civic leaders working together can help business to prosper across the country.</p><p> </p><p>The review is ongoing and we are currently taking views on how LEPs can support businesses deliver an effective and vibrant economy. We intend to conclude the review in the coming months.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-30T16:23:59.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830541/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830541/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Local Enterprise Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, what the timescale is for the completion of the Government’s review into Local Enterprise Partnerships.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","125069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830542","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-30","<p>The costs of branded medicines are controlled by the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme and the statutory scheme for branded medicines. Liothyronine is an unbranded generic medicine. For unbranded generic medicines, the Department encourages competition between suppliers to keep prices down. In primary care, community pharmacies are incentivised to source products at the lowest possible cost and in secondary care, competitive tenders ensure value-for-money to the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>Liothyronine is currently the subject of an investigation by the Competition and Markets Authority, which has provisionally found that the single supplier of the product abused its dominant position to overcharge the NHS by millions for liothyronine tablets. A provisional decision does not necessarily lead to an infringement decision. Where companies have breached competition law, the Department will seek damages and invest that money back into the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>Medicines legislation requires that only medicines licensed for use in the United Kingdom can be marketed in the UK.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","125067","2018-01-30T17:14:17.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830542/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830542/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-25","Liothyronine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to reduce the cost of liothyronine by procuring the drug from foreign suppliers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","125070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830543","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>I would refer to our response to questions 120177 and 120170 and would restate that the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy regularly engages with the major business representative organisations, including the Federation of Small Businesses and the British Chambers of Commerce, on a wide range of issues.</p><p>We are already engaging directly with private and public sector business on a variety of issues, through a series of regional roundtables. This involves businesses around England and including most recently, Stockton on Tees in the North East.</p><p>The review of productivity will focus on what actions could be most effective in improving productivity and growth of SMEs. We will announce the policies we intend to take forward, following this review, in autumn 2018.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","125072","2018-01-30T16:23:00.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830543/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830543/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Small Businesses: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 22 December 2017 to Question 120177, on Small Businesses: Productivity, what the Department’s programme of engagement will consist of.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","125071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830544","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>I would refer to our response to questions 120177 and 120170 and would restate that the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy regularly engages with the major business representative organisations, including the Federation of Small Businesses and the British Chambers of Commerce, on a wide range of issues.</p><p>We are already engaging directly with private and public sector business on a variety of issues, through a series of regional roundtables. This involves businesses around England and including most recently, Stockton on Tees in the North East.</p><p>The review of productivity will focus on what actions could be most effective in improving productivity and growth of SMEs. We will announce the policies we intend to take forward, following this review, in autumn 2018.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","125071","2018-01-30T16:23:00Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830544/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830544/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Small Businesses: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 22 December 2017 to Question 120177, on Small Businesses: Productivity, what representations the Department has received from businesses and business organisations in the North East.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","125072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830545","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-31","<p>There is no single measure through which a ‘global leadership’ position will be determined. To measure the success of the Industrial Strategy, the White Paper announced the creation of the Industrial Strategy Council. This will be formed by a group of independent experts that will develop a series of success measures to help determine the success of the delivery of the strategy against our stated goals.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-01-31T17:57:14.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830545/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830545/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 21 December 2017 to Question 120176, how the Department measures and defines a global leadership position.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","125073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830546","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-01","<p>We announced an additional investment of £725m in the second wave of challenges in the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund at the Autumn Budget 2017. The technologies and future industries that these challenges support will need to combine the strengths of businesses and researchers across the UK. Wherever they are, they will be able to compete for ISCF funding.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-02-01T15:22:22.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830546/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830546/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the geographical spread of recently announced spending commitments drawn from the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","125074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830547","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>Some disabled people are able to receive the Warm Home Discount currently if they are in receipt of qualifying benefits or if they meet the criteria determined by their energy supplier. Government will be consulting shortly on changes to the Warm Home Discount for 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>We will also be consulting soon on the Energy Company Obligation proposing reforms to focus the whole scheme on low income and vulnerable households.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-30T17:30:30.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830547/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830547/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","Warm Home Discount Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of reforming the Warm Home Discount so that it more effectively target supports to disabled people who are experiencing high energy costs.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","125075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830548","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-01","<p>Officials from the Department for International Development and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in Burma regularly raise issues of safety and security of displaced people and access for humanitarian assistance to the Burmese government at local and national levels. These discussions are generally not specific to those returning from the Thai-Burma border, where returns have been few.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-01T13:51:51.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830548/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830548/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Burma: Thailand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 23 January to Question 123667, what discussions she has had from the Burmese Government on the safety and security of (a) refugees and (b) internally displaced people returning from camps on either side of the Thai-Burma border.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830549","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-01","<p>The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees stated that the total verified refugee population in the camps in Thailand in December 2017 was 99,956. The Myanmar Humanitarian Response Plan for 2018 recognises 5,616 displaced persons in Kayin State, 15,006 in Shan State, and 91,739 in Kachin State, in Eastern Burma. It notes that “accurate IDP numbers are difficult to ascertain” in the South East, beyond the 5,616 recently displaced in Kayin.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-01T13:53:45.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830549/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830549/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Burma: Internally Displaced People and Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 23 January to Question 123667, what recent estimate she has made of the (a) number of Burmese refugees in camps in Thailand and (b) number of internally displaced people in camps in Eastern Burma.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830550","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-01","<p>The Department for International Development (DFID) reviewed the level of funding for refugees on the Thai-Burma border in 2017. Between 2012-16 DFID provided £1.35 million per year to International Rescue Committee (IRC) and The Border Consortium (TBC) for the refugee camps. Following review, our funding for 2017 was £1.1 million. The reduction in funding was proportionally smaller than the decrease in the number of refugees in the camps since 2012. DFID’s support to displaced and conflict-affected communities in South East Burma is now largely through our contribution to livelihoods and health multi-donor trust funds rather than through our humanitarian programme. We continue to keep needs under review.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-01T13:58:06.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830550/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830550/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Burma: Thailand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 23 January to Question 123667 on Burma: Thailand, when her Department last reviewed the level of funding it has allocated to support for internally-displaced people and refugees on the Thai-Burma border; and what the timescale was for that funding.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830551","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-01","<p>My Department is aware some agencies and NGOs have not previously followed international standards in terms of borehole drilling depths and location of latrines in relation to water sources. My officials followed up in November and December with the appropriate coordination groups, such as the Water, Sanitation and Hygiene Sector Group and Senior Coordinator’s Office, to reinforce the need for all agencies and NGOs to adhere to minimum standards in this area to protect people’s health.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-01T14:02:50.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830551/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830551/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Bangladesh: Migrant Camps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2017 to Question on Bangladesh: Rohingya, what recent discussions she has had with her Bangladeshi counterparts on the proximity of (a) borehole drilling and (b) toilets to water sources in refugee camps.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830552","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>The immediate task is to support those building evidence and testimony. The Government is considering how to support effective co-ordination, through an international or local mechanism, of those organisations already collecting testimony in Bangladesh. The UK will provide capacity building to Bangladeshi stakeholders on gathering and preserving evidence of sexual violence, in line with the International Protocol on Investigation and Documentation of Sexual Violence in Conflict.</p><p>The UK co-sponsored the resolution at the Human Rights Council in March 2017 that set up a Fact Finding Mission to look into the human rights situation in Burma, including Rakhine. It will issue its initial report in mid-March, and final report in September 2018. Any judgement on whether crimes under international law have occurred is a matter for judicial decision, rather than governments or non-judicial bodies, but the UK government will work closely with the international community, to ensure any wrongdoers are brought to account.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-02-02T14:25:07.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830552/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830552/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-25","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that there is an independent international investigation of the allegations against the Burmese military for their actions against the Rohingya community in Burma.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830553","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-30","<p>The situation in Burma was not on the agenda for the December 2017 meeting of the EU Foreign Affairs Council. In the Answer [cited by the Honourable Gentleman], the Government committed to considering additional measures with EU partners if the Burmese authorities failed to heed the calls of the UN Security Council Presidential Statement of 6 November. It was not possible to make this determination in time to allow discussion at the December Foreign Affairs Council, as the UN Secretary-General did not report to the Security Council until the following day.</p><p>Following the Secretary-General's report, we are assessing, with EU partners, whether targeted EU sanctions against individual senior military officers would be effective in changing the behaviour of the Burmese military.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-30T16:45:04.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830553/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830553/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-25","Burma: Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 1 December 2017 to Question 115475 on Burma: travel restrictions, whether he raised Burma and formalised travel sanctions on Burmese military leaders at the EU Foreign Affairs Council in December 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830554","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-01","<p>We are one of the largest bilateral donors to the Rohingya refugee crisis in Bangladesh, with a total contribution of £59 million, and we have been working with the Government of Bangladesh to facilitate the important work of NGOs. In Burma we continue to press for better humanitarian access. We are working through the Red Cross and the World Food Programme to provide some emergency assistance but we would like to do more. Many urgent needs are not being met because of government restrictions on access.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-01T14:04:09.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830554/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830554/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","Bangladesh and Burma: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the levels of humanitarian access available to organisations operating in Bangladesh and Burma.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830555","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-30","<p>The capacity needs assessment in Bangladesh was completed on 3 December 2017. It provided valuable recommendations for the government on issues of political engagement, international coordination, support for survivors, evidence gathering and prevention of further crimes including sexual violence and human trafficking. The FCO and DFID are working closely together to action the recommendations, with most now already being implemented in partnership with domestic and international partners.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-30T17:29:22.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830555/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830555/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-25","Burma: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department’s capacity needs assessment on the investigation and documentation of sexual violence in Burma has been completed.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830556","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-30","<p>The UK has discussed the situation in detail with the United States, all other main donors, and host Governments in the context of the recent United Nations Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA) Advisory Commission. The UK has highlighted our concern about the impact on the activities of UNRWA that any unexpected reductions or delays in predicted donor disbursements might have.</p><p> </p><p>My officials are working closely with UNRWA, the United States, and other European Union partners to understand the risks to UNRWA’s programmes and to ensure the continuity of services for Palestinian refugees. The UK is concerned about the impact on UNRWA’s activities whenever unexpected reductions or delays in predicted donor disbursements occur and, in particular, how this may disproportionally affect the most vulnerable refugees. We are liaising with UNRWA on their plans for service continuity. UNRWA has publically stated their determination to continue services in all their fields of operations.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-30T17:26:23.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830556/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830556/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-25","USA: UNRWA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with his US counterpart on that Administration’s decision to withhold funding to the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestinian refugees; and what assessment she has made of the effect of that decision on programmes operating in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830557","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Modernising Defence Programme will deliver the right military capability for today's, and future threats, while making sure that Defence is sustainable and affordable.</p><p>I have been speaking regularly to the Chancellor since arriving at the Ministry of Defence and will continue to do so as the programme progresses.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","125092","2018-01-31T16:22:04.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830557/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830557/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Defence: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Oral Statement of 25 January 2018, on his Department's Modernising Defence Programme, whether the value of identified savings his Department requires is to be realised as part of current budget assumptions.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830558","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-30","<p>National statistics on the number of children in relative low income are set out in the annual &quot;Households Below Average Income&quot; publication. The number and proportion of children in relative low income is not available at local authority or constituency level in this publication because the survey sample sizes are too small to support the production of robust estimates at this geography.</p><p>Latest 3-year estimates for the North West of the proportion and number of children in low income are available in Table 4.16ts and Table 4.17ts in the file “4_children_timeseries_risk” from this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/599136/hbai-2015-2016-supporting-ods-files.zip" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/599136/hbai-2015-2016-supporting-ods-files.zip</a></p><p>Impact Assessments of policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Act of 2016 were published in 2015. Evidence shows work is the best route out of poverty; nearly three-quarters of children from workless families moved out of poverty when their parents entered into full-time work. Children in workless households are five time more likely to be in poverty than those in households where all adults were working. Welfare reforms are designed to incentivise parents to make the choice to move into and progress in work.</p><p>This Government is committed to action that tackles the root causes of poverty and disadvantage with policies that incentivise employment as the best route out of poverty. In <em>Improving Lives: Helping Workless Families</em>, we set out a framework for a continued focus on improving children’s long-term outcomes. This includes nine national indicators to track progress in tackling the disadvantages that affect families and children. Four of these measures are set out in primary legislation which places a duty on the Government report annually to Parliament on the parental worklessness and educational attainment indicators. Data on the non-statutory indicators will also be published each year.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-30T12:09:50.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830558/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830558/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Poverty: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of recent changes in welfare provision on the number of children living in poverty in the Borough of Rochdale.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","125086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830559","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Programme will consist of four strands of work:</p><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Looking at the Department's Operating Model</strong> - delivering a stronger Head Office which has the right leadership.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Making sure Defence is an efficient Department</strong> - so we can assure everyone that every penny goes to the right things, reducing duplication and adopting new approaches to deliver a more modern organisation.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Recognising the contribution defence industry makes to our nation's economic prosperity </strong>- We need to get the most out of our defence industry and promote our commercial interests at home and abroad as we create a global Britain. We will assess how the Ministry of Defence can improve on strategic supplier management and improve its commercial capability.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><strong>And, most importantly, the final strand</strong> - making sure our Armed Forces have the right capabilities to tackle the increasing threats we face on the global stage. This will look at the threat picture, and that our Armed Forces have the right equipment, training and workforce and force generation on a sustainable footing.</li></ul>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-01-31T16:19:13.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830559/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830559/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Defence: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Oral Statement of 25 January 2018, on his Department's Modernising Defence Programme, if he will provide further information on the work to be undertaken under the strands outlined in that programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830560","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-30","<p>On the East Coast Mainline, Intercity Express Trains (IETs) are capable of achieving 125mph in electric traction and in diesel mode a balancing speed (determined by a number of variables such as track gradient and passenger load) of approximately 115mph under test conditions. The average speed of the IETs will be dependent on the route, stopping pattern and dwell times at stations; we therefore do not hold this information. With respect to Hull Trains, it is not possible to comment on the performance of any trains not procured by the Department.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-30T11:34:43.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830560/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830560/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) maximum capable speed and (b) average expected speed of the trains will be in (i) diesel and (ii) electric mode in optimal conditions of the new bi-modal trains to be introduced in the Virgin Trains East Coast franchise and the Hull Trains open access operator in 2018-19 to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","125088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830561","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>The UK is defended by an integrated air defence system that includes Quick Reaction Alert Typhoon aircraft held at continuous readiness, 24 hours a day, and air surveillance and control facilities that are fully interoperable with NATO allies. Additionally, ground based air defence is provided by Army Air Defence Regiments and Royal Navy Type 45 Destroyers have an air defence capability.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence keeps its equipment requirements under continuous review to ensure it can react to the evolving defence environment.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-30T14:10:43.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830561/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830561/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will list the UK's air defence assets; and whether he plans to replace current equipment.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830562","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-02","<p>As set out in the Planning Policy for Traveller Sites, the Government has asked local planning authorities, as part of their local plan, to identify and update annually a five year supply of specific, deliverable sites to meet local need for traveller sites. Local planning authorities should set pitch and plot targets to address the accommodation needs of travellers in their area.</p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework clarifies that local plans will be examined by an independent inspector whose role is to assess whether the plan has been prepared in accordance with the Duty to Cooperate, legal and procedural requirements, and whether it is sound. A local planning authority should submit a plan for examination which is consistent with national policy, including the Planning Policy for Traveller Sites.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-02T14:47:23.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830562/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830562/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-25","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure local authorities allocate land in their local plans to meet their estimated need for new sites for Travellers.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","125090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830563","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>The spend to the end of December 2017 (inclusive of VAT) on the Challenger Life Extension Programme is £38.2 million and on the Warrior Capability Sustainment Programme is £401 million.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-30T14:05:20.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830563/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830563/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Warrior Armoured Vehicle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department has spent to date on the (a) Challenger 2 Life Extension Programme and (b) Warrior Capability Sustainment Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830564","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Modernising Defence Programme will deliver the right military capability for today's, and future threats, while making sure that Defence is sustainable and affordable.</p><p>I have been speaking regularly to the Chancellor since arriving at the Ministry of Defence and will continue to do so as the programme progresses.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","125085","2018-01-31T16:22:04.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830564/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830564/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Defence: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Oral Statement of 25 January 2018, on his Department's Modernising Defence Programme, whether that programme will be fiscally neutral.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830565","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-30","<p>As Northern Trains do not run direct services between Hull and Manchester, and the new rolling stock on TransPennine Express is not being allocated to the Hull to Manchester route, the new rolling stock being introduced on the two franchises will not affect train timings for this journey.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-30T11:41:38.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830565/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830565/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-25","Rolling Stock: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether new rolling stock being introduced on the (a) northern and (b) TransPennine Express franchises will reduce journey times between Hull and Manchester.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","125093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830566","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>The eligibility for passported benefits is often, but not always, linked to entitlement to income-related benefits such as Income Support, income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance, income-related Employment and Support Allowance, Universal Credit and Pension Credit. The introduction of Support for Mortgage Interest Loans in April 2018 will not change these criteria.</p><p> </p><p>In some instances, claimants who are treated as receiving the income-related based benefit solely due to eligibility for SMI will no longer be automatically entitled to all ‘passported’ benefits. Many of these claimants will remain eligible to a number of passported benefits on the grounds of age or low income but will usually need to apply for them directly.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-31T16:14:58.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830566/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830566/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the removal of Support for Mortgage Interest as part of benefit entitlement from April 2018 will affect entitlement to passported benefits such as help with health costs, free school meals, sure start maternity grant and the warm home discount scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","125094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830567","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Modernising Defence Programme will deliver the right military capability for today's, and future threats, while making sure that Defence is sustainable and affordable.</p><p>We aim to engage widely throughout the process, and to listen to a range of expert views.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","125106","2018-01-31T16:08:43.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830567/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830567/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Defence: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Oral Statement of 25 January 2018, on his Department's Modernising Defence Programme, if he will rule out reductions to the army's (a) armoured infantry brigades and (b) army aviation brigades.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830568","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>Department has not carried out any face to face explanations of Support for Mortgage Interest loans.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-31T14:30:54.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830568/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830568/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many face to face explanations of the change to Support for Mortgage Interest loan payments her Department has carried out supplementary to the telephone and online contact with SERCO.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","125096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830569","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-01","<p>First-time buyers of shared ownership property who choose to pay SDLT at purchase on the whole market value of the property can benefit from the relief. If the property is worth £300,000 or less, there will be no SDLT to pay. According to Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government data, the median shared ownership market value is £220,000.</p><p> </p><p>Where market value treatment does not apply, or has not been opted for, the first-time buyers’ relief cannot be claimed. There is already a special SDLT treatment given to purchasers of new shared ownership properties. Purchasers can choose to pay SDLT on the initial portion purchased with a further SDLT charge if they buy the remaining share in the future.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-02-01T14:25:17.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830569/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830569/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-25","Shared Ownership: Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of whether purchasers of shared ownership properties are benefiting from the the stamp duty exemption announced in Autumn Budget 2017; and whether purchasers who opt to stamp duty on the value of the initial share benefit from that exemption.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","125097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830570","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Department estimates that the total cost of implementing Support for Mortgage Interest loans will be £20.47m. The ongoing administrative costs are estimated to be £2.20m a year.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-31T14:16:15.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830570/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830570/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the cost of implementing the change of Support for Mortgage Interest from a benefit to a loan; and the ongoing administration of that loan.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","125098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830571","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-01","<p>The Government is currently conducting a Tailored Review of the Criminal Cases Review Commission (CCRC).</p><p> </p><p>The review will examine, among other things, the functions and form of the CCRC, its governance and performance.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the review, contributions have been sought from people and organisations that have an involvement with, or interest in, the CCRC. Analysis of these contributions will form the basis of the recommendations and the final report.</p><p>The final report will be published in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-01T14:42:26.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830571/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830571/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-25","Criminal Cases Review Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has plans to review the Criminal Cases Review Commission in terms of its accountability, Independence, efficiency and ability to investigate new evidence.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","125099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830572","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>This is a commercial matter for the companies involved, however the Government is closely monitoring the situation. If necessary, the Government can intervene in takeovers on public interest grounds, covering national security, financial stability or media plurality.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-30T16:23:20.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830572/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830572/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","GKN: Melrose","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the potential takeover of GKN on the UK's automotive and aerospace industries.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830573","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>GKN announced on 12 January that it had been approached by Melrose. Since then I have spoken on an impartial basis to both companies, and will continue to monitor the situation closely.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-30T16:23:05.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830573/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830573/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","GKN: Melrose","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he was made aware of the attempted takeover of GKN by Melrose; and whether he has met with any of the parties involved.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830574","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-30","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave him today to Question 125100.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-30T17:50:49.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830574/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830574/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-25","GKN: Melrose","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect on the UK economy of the potential takeover of GKN by Melrose.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830575","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-01","<p>The impact of Universal Credit cannot be considered in isolation. Tackling child poverty and disadvantage is a priority for this government and Universal Credit is a key component of a broader strategy to move Britain to a higher wage, lower welfare and lower tax society. This strategy includes increasing the personal tax allowance and introducing the national living wage.</p><p>In line with this strategy, Universal Credit is designed to strengthen incentives for parents to move into and progress in work, and it is working. Universal Credit claimants move into work faster and spend more time looking for work.</p><p>In addition, Universal Credit provides improved support for childcare for parents, enabling them to reclaim up to 85% of their eligible childcare costs, which is expected to help 500,000 additional families at a cost of around £350m per year.</p><p>At the Budget, the Chancellor announced a number of further improvements to Universal Credit which will help ensure that claimants are supported until they receive their first monthly Universal Credit payment.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-02-01T14:21:05.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830575/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830575/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Universal Credit: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment her Department has made of the effect of the roll-out of universal credit on levels of child poverty.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830576","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-30","<p>The text messages that were sent to parents in December 2017 cost approximately £1,400. These messages were part of wider communications to encourage parents to apply, or reconfirm their eligibility for 30 hours free childcare before the start of the spring term. Over 326,000 30 hours codes were issued for the spring term.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is investing more in childcare than ever before. Tax-Free Childcare is one part of that childcare support and is aimed at working parents. Foster carers already receive funding for the care of their foster child from local authorities. Local authorities are best placed to individually assess what is in the best interests of fostered children. Where they judge that it is in the best interests of a fostered child, local authorities can fund childcare on a discretionary basis.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","125107","2018-01-30T13:10:54.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830576/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830576/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-25","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the answer of 8 January 2018 to Question 120802, on children:day care, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential financial benefits to foster parents of making tax-free childcare available for fostered children.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","125104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830577","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-01","<p>The proportion of people in absolute poverty is at record lows. Since 2010 there are 600,000 fewer people in absolute poverty, including 200,000 fewer children. Work is the most effective way out of poverty and unemployment has not been lower since 1975. There is more to do and the government is committed to supporting families with the cost of living. At the Autumn Budget, the government announced that from this April the National Living Wage will increase by 4.4% and the personal allowance to £11,850. The government has also frozen fuel duty for the eighth successive year. Last April, the government published its “Improving Lives: Helping Workless Families” strategy. This focused on measures that tackle the root causes of poverty, in particular workless households and educational attainment.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-02-01T11:58:39.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830577/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830577/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-25","Poverty: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the cost of living on levels of child poverty.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","125105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830578","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-31","<p>The Modernising Defence Programme will deliver the right military capability for today's, and future threats, while making sure that Defence is sustainable and affordable.</p><p>We aim to engage widely throughout the process, and to listen to a range of expert views.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","125095","2018-01-31T16:08:43.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830578/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830578/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Defence: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Oral Statement of 25 January 2018, on his Department's Modernising Defence Programme, whether a reduction in personnel and resources in the Educational and Training Services Branch of the Army's Adjutant General's Corps will form part of that programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830579","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-30","<p>The text messages that were sent to parents in December 2017 cost approximately £1,400. These messages were part of wider communications to encourage parents to apply, or reconfirm their eligibility for 30 hours free childcare before the start of the spring term. Over 326,000 30 hours codes were issued for the spring term.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is investing more in childcare than ever before. Tax-Free Childcare is one part of that childcare support and is aimed at working parents. Foster carers already receive funding for the care of their foster child from local authorities. Local authorities are best placed to individually assess what is in the best interests of fostered children. Where they judge that it is in the best interests of a fostered child, local authorities can fund childcare on a discretionary basis.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","125104","2018-01-30T13:10:54.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830579/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830579/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-25","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the answer of 8 January 2018 to Question 120803, on children: day care, what the cost to the public purse of sending those text messages was; and what proportion of the people who received a text message successfully reapplied for an eligibility code.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","125107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830580","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-30","<p>We are committed to agreeing and publishing sector deals as soon as both sides are content to do so. DCMS continue to work closely with BEIS and the Creative Industries to deliver an ambitious deal to increase growth and productivity.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","125109","2018-01-30T16:26:26.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830580/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830580/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-25","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether he plans to publish the creative industries sector deal before 1 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","125108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830581","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-30","<p>We are committed to agreeing and publishing sector deals as soon as both sides are content to do so. DCMS continue to work closely with BEIS and the Creative Industries to deliver an ambitious deal to increase growth and productivity.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","125108","2018-01-30T16:26:26.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830581/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830581/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-25","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy, and Industrial Strategy on the progress of the creative industries sector deal.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","125109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830582","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>£50 million will be invested by the government to create more high quality school-based provision, as explained in the Social Mobility Action Plan, available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/667690/Social_Mobility_Action_Plan_-_for_printing.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/667690/Social_Mobility_Action_Plan_-_for_printing.pdf</a>.</p><p>We will announce more details of our plans for distributing this investment, and the process that will be involved, in due course.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-30T17:03:13.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830582/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830582/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-25","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 18 December 2017 to Question 119402, when his Department will begin to invest that £50 million.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","125110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830583","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-02","<p>Two complementary market analysis assessments have been produced by the Government to date. The first assessment was derived from three independent studies, conducted in parallel, by market analysts from the Ministry of Defence (MOD), the UK Defence Solutions Centre and an independent consultancy firm. Supporting evidence from this first assessment was then further refined in an assessment carried out by the Department for International Trade and the MOD. Analysis is ongoing as the market continues to evolve.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-02-02T14:53:48.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830583/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830583/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-25","Type 31 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2018 to Question 123285, on Type 31 Frigates, what the evidential basis was for the Government's assessment that there is a potential light frigate market of around 40 ships over the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830584","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>Our delivery contractor, Childcare Works, continues to support and work closely with local authorities through the first year of national delivery, ensuring learning and best practice is shared across local authorities. Part of this support work includes the ongoing buddying scheme, which continues to progress well. Once the matches have been officially confirmed, this information will be made publically available.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-30T16:57:33.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830584/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830584/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-25","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2017 to Question 118334, on children: day care, on what date he plans to make an announcement on the buddy system for local authorities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","125112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830585","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>Full guidance is made available to all DWP staff on what action is required when a claimant moves to a different area. To assist with this process, claimants are made aware of what steps they need to take to ensure that there are no delays in their payments. Work coaches and colleagues in service centres work hard to ensure that any errors made are kept to a minimum and rectified promptly.</p><p> </p><p>If a claimant moves out of a postcode area where Universal Credit Full Service is delivered into a postcode area where it is not, their Universal Credit Full Service claim will remain open.</p><p> </p><p>Their previous office would retain ownership of their records and, in collaboration with the new site, work with the claimant to move them closer to or into work. The claim would then transfer fully when the new office the claimant is now attending begins to deliver Universal Credit Full Service.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","125116","2018-01-31T16:28:38.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830585/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830585/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment she has made of errors in benefit payments resulting from claimants moving from one job centre catchment area to another, particularly when one jobcentre operates universal credit and the other does not.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","125113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830586","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-30","<p>An ageing society means that we need to reach a longer-term sustainable settlement for social care. This is why the Government has committed to publishing a Green Paper by summer 2018 setting out its proposals for reform.</p><p> </p><p>This will include consulting on a limit on the care costs that individuals face.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-30T14:35:04.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830586/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830586/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-25","Social Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department's upcoming consultation on social care will propose specific amounts for a cap on the amount someone would have to pay towards their own care.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","125114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830587","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-30","<p>The Government has committed to publishing a Green Paper by summer 2018 setting out its proposals for reform of the social care system.</p><p> </p><p>While the fees charged to a self-funder is a contractual arrangement between self-funding residents and care homes, we are also considering recommendations from the Competition and Markets Authority who highlighted the need for care home providers to be more transparent about their prices.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-30T14:36:36.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830587/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830587/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-25","Care Homes: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department’s upcoming consultation on social care will include a review of prices charged by care homes to people funding their own care.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","125115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830588","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-31","<p>Full guidance is made available to all DWP staff on what action is required when a claimant moves to a different area. To assist with this process, claimants are made aware of what steps they need to take to ensure that there are no delays in their payments. Work coaches and colleagues in service centres work hard to ensure that any errors made are kept to a minimum and rectified promptly.</p><p> </p><p>If a claimant moves out of a postcode area where Universal Credit Full Service is delivered into a postcode area where it is not, their Universal Credit Full Service claim will remain open.</p><p> </p><p>Their previous office would retain ownership of their records and, in collaboration with the new site, work with the claimant to move them closer to or into work. The claim would then transfer fully when the new office the claimant is now attending begins to deliver Universal Credit Full Service.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","125113","2018-01-31T16:28:38.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830588/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/830588/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-25","Jobcentres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance her Department has issued to jobcentres on processing claimants who have moved from one job centre catchment area to another, particularly when a claimant moves to or from a universal credit full service rollout area to one that does not yet offer universal credit.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","125116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829548","Cabinet Office","true","2018-02-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply and I will place a copy of their letter in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-02-01T12:03:13.597Z","2018-02-20T17:30:54.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829548/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829548/answer","HL5053 (1).pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829548/answer",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829548/answer/previousversion/38579","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829548/answer/previousversion/38579","HL5053 LY.doc","UKSA Response ","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-24","Death","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the total number of deaths in the UK in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829549","Home Office","false","2018-01-31","<p>The minimum salary thresholds were set following consultation with the independent Migration Advisory Committee and are based on pay scales published by the NHS.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-01-31T13:45:19.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829549/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829549/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-24","Migrant Workers: Doctors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to reduce the Home Office salary threshold for granting visas in respect of overseas doctors seeking employment in UK hospitals; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829551","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Ministry of Justice, Department of Health and Social Care, and their agencies, work in close partnership to oversee the commissioning and delivery of healthcare in prisons.</p><p> </p><p>The National Partnership Agreement for the collaborative commissioning and delivery of healthcare services in prisons in England enables joint working and discussions between departments for the effective oversight of prison healthcare services. This agreement between the Ministry of Justice, Department of Health and Social Care, Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service, NHS England and Public Health England, sets out the shared strategic intent and joint commitments in the commissioning, enabling and delivery of healthcare services in adult prisons. The current agreement is subject to review and an updated version will be published in April 2018.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-02-05T16:42:06.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829551/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829551/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-24","Prisons: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions have taken place between the Ministry of Justice and the Department of Health and Social Care concerning the provision of adequate healthcare in prisons following recent reports.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829552","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>Health and Wellbeing Boards bring together local authorities, the National Health Service and other partners to agree local priorities. They carry out Joint Strategic Needs Assessments which consider the needs of offenders. The Government is not proposing to involve itself in this local priority setting.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-02-07T16:55:04.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829552/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829552/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-24","Prisons: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to encourage local authorities with responsibility for scrutinising health services to exercise that function in relation to the provision of health care within custodial institutions in their area.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829553","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-01","<p>Throughout the period between 2004 and 2014 the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and the Department for Trade and Industry (and its successors) agreed that the original classification of the FRC as a public body should, if possible, be revised. The Department worked with the FRC to seek its reclassification from the Office for National Statistics on a number of occasions. The justification for this was based on wider Government policy on public bodies and the development of the FRC’s functions.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-01T15:30:40.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829553/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829553/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-24","Financial Reporting Council","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) sought to resist the classification decision of the National Accounts Classification Committee in 2004 that the FRC was a public body; if so, whether they supported that resistance; and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bowles of Berkhamsted",,"Baroness Bowles of Berkhamsted","HL5057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829554","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-01","<p>We are informed by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) that their total spend on external legal advice on all issues arising out the FRC’s classification as a public body is £6,482.70 inclusive of VAT. This is a cumulative figure covering the period from 2004 through to 2017.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-01T15:32:26.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829554/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/829554/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-24","Financial Reporting Council","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the total cost of external legal advice sought by the Financial Reporting Council regarding the classification decision of the National Accounts Classification Committee, including any attempts at reclassification.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bowles of Berkhamsted",,"Baroness Bowles of Berkhamsted","HL5058"
